{% if exploit_type == "missing-network-policies" or exploit_type == "all" %}
## NetworkPolicy Rules
1. Always include a default-deny-all policy first (podSelector: {}, policyTypes: [Ingress, Egress]).
2. Add one policy per service with explicit `from:` podSelector selectors on ingress rules.
   Never use an empty `from:` list — that allows all pods.
3. Every pod needs DNS egress to kube-dns on UDP/53.
4. Services with no listed callers get `ingress: []` (fully blocked).
5. Label all policies: `app.kubernetes.io/managed-by: kimera`.
6. Base ingress `from:` selectors on the provided topology.
   If a service has no topology entry, allow ingress from all pods in the namespace (fail-open).
7. For egress: allow same-namespace traffic + DNS only.
{% endif %}

{% if exploit_type == "privileged-containers" or exploit_type == "all" %}
## Privileged Container Hardening Rules
1. Set `securityContext.privileged: false` on every container.
2. Set `securityContext.allowPrivilegeEscalation: false` on every container.
3. Set `securityContext.runAsNonRoot: true` on every container.
4. Never delete containers, change images, or modify replicas.
5. Label all resources: `app.kubernetes.io/managed-by: kimera`.
{% endif %}

{% if exploit_type == "dangerous-capabilities" or exploit_type == "all" %}
## Capabilities Hardening Rules
1. Drop ALL capabilities: `securityContext.capabilities.drop: ["ALL"]`.
2. Remove any added dangerous capabilities (SYS_ADMIN, NET_ADMIN, SYS_PTRACE, etc.).
3. Only add back capabilities that are strictly required for the container to function.
4. Never delete containers, change images, or modify replicas.
5. Label all resources: `app.kubernetes.io/managed-by: kimera`.
{% endif %}

